      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i have a physics exam coming up and i'm struggling a bit with the concept of quantum entanglement. can you give me a concise, non-mathematical summary of what it actually is and how it's different from just regular classical correlation? thanks",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Quantum entanglement is a phenomenon where two or more particles become so deeply connected that the state of one instantly influences the state of the other, no matter how far apart they are. It's like having a pair of magical, invisible gloves that are always linked together. When you put on one glove, the other glove changes its state instantly, even if it's on the other side of the world. This is different from classical correlation, where two objects might seem related, but their connection is more like a chain of dominoes falling one after another, rather than an instant, magical link. In classical correlation, the connection is limited by the speed of light, but in quantum entanglement, it's as if the gloves are talking to each other faster than the speed of light, defying our usual understanding of space and time. So, while classical correlation is like a predictable, slow dance, quantum entanglement is a spontaneous, mysterious tango that leaves even the most seasoned dancers gobsmacked.",
      "source": "target",
